With your latest update, it seems that the Python script is by another &quot;master&quot; application. And it might hint at a possibility to improve the overall architecture. But without knowing more about the &quot;master&quot; program, it is hard to say.

If that is the case, it is up to that &quot;master&quot; program to pass the time to the Python script.

One important this is that `datetime.now()` will always return the *current* time. The only way to have the time &quot;frozen&quot; is by saving the value somewhere. If everything runs in the same process it can be a variable. If - like seemingly in your case - is spans multiple distinct processes, you might need to save the value into persisten storage (like plain-text) file. But this opens up risks of race-conditions (what if two processes run at the same time and want to create the same file twice). It is a fragile approach. I would only do this if absolutely necessary.

A slightly better approach is to have the master-application deal with this alone and pass the values as arguments to the sub-processes.

Again, as the detail of the master application is missing I am forced to take an educated guess. That guess is that the master program is a bash-script executing the other processes (I might be wrong).

So inside the Python script you need to read the value from the CLI argument. This can be done by accessing `sys.argv` but I *STRONGLY* suggest using `argparse` instead. It is only marginally more work but *WAY* more maintainable (and it gives you a `--help` argument for free):

```
from argparse import ArgumentParser

def parse_args():
    parser = ArgumentParser()
    parser.add_argument(&#39;starttime&#39;)
    return parser.parse_args()

cli_args = parse_args()
timestring = cli_args.starttime
```

Next, the &quot;master&quot; application needs to pass this value into the child script:

```
